04202nam a2200553Ia 9780231559492DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2023032863  a97802315594927 a10.7312/mcki212642doi  a(DE-B1597)690057  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN4900.S3bM35 2024 7aLIT0240502bisacsh04a051qOCoLC223/eng/202308041 aMcKible, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCirculating Jim Crow :bThe Saturday Evening Post and the War Against Black Modernity /cAdam McKible. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter One GEORGE HORACE LORIMER AND RISING JIM CROW -- tChapter Two LITERARY ASPIRATION AND INTIMATE MINSTRELSY -- tChapter Three IRVIN S. COBB: MAKING THE NEW NEGRO OLD AGAIN -- tChapter Four HUGH WILEY, EDWARD CHRISTOPHER WILLIAMS, AND BLACK DOUGHBOYS -- tChapter Five OCTAVUS ROY COHEN, THE MIDNIGHT MOTION PICTURE COMPANY, AND THE SHADOWS OF JIM CROW -- tChapter Six THE END OF THE LORIMER ERA -- tEPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early twentieth century, the Saturday Evening Post was perhaps the most popular and influential magazine in the United States, establishing literary reputations and shaping American culture. In the popular imagination, it is best remembered for Norman Rockwell’s covers, which nostalgically depicted a wholesome and idyllic American way of life. But beneath those covers lurked a more troubling reality. Under the direction of its longtime editor, George Horace Lorimer, the magazine helped justify racism and white supremacy. It published works by white authors that made heavy use of paternalistic tropes and demeaning humor, portraying Jim Crow segregation and violence as simple common sense.Circulating Jim Crow demonstrates how the Post used stereotypical dialect fiction to promulgate white supremacist ideology and dismiss Black achievements, citizenship, and humanity. Adam McKible tells the story of Lorimer’s rise to prominence and examines the white authors who provided the editor and his readers with the caricatures they craved. He also explores how Black writers of the Harlem Renaissance pushed back against the Post and its commodified racism. McKible places the erstwhile household names who wrote for the magazine in conversation with figures such as Paul Laurence Dunbar, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Ann Petry, W. E. B. Du Bois, and William Faulkner. Revealing the role of the Saturday Evening Post in normalizing racism for millions of readers, this book also offers a new understanding of how Black writers challenged Jim Crow ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican Americans in popular culture. 0aAfrican AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican periodicalsxHistoryy20th century. 0aHarlem Renaissance. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mcki2126440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231559492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231559492/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles